Hello Matt-

Apologies for the delay in responding to this. I flagged it as something to
be thought about and replied to, and then it scrolled off my screen into
email purgatory. 

I do think that HyperNEAT can exploit non-geometric regularities to a
problem. Imagine a medical diagnostic classification problem such as
declaring the risk of heart attack. Your inputs are variables that do not
have any geometry to them (weight, age, number of years smoked, presence of
gene x, etc). Imagine further that these variables could be grouped into
group A and B. 

Group A needs to be put through the following complex
function/transformation: 1-2-3-4-5  (each number could represent a node+link
that performs a mathematical operation).

Group B needs to be put through 6-2-3-4-7.

A direct encoding would have to independently create the 2-3-4 module each
time it needs to be used (twice in this example). HyperNEAT, by virtue of
being a generative/indirect encoding, only has to create it once and can use
it many times. 

One could, of course, envision that there are 100 groups that each need the
2-3-4 module, at which point the benefit of the generative encoding becomes
more obvious.

Do you (and others) agree that this is an example of HyperNEAT outperforming
neat because it exploits a regularity of the problem that is non-geometric?



